reviews.review_text:
Cumulative weight
A show that was worth the run buildup. We walked in to discover Hornsby absent. This didn't seem fortuitous, and it did change the sound, yet there was an electrical charge and this became the best night of the run. It made me glad I had abruptly committed to December shows. Also the best show of late '90, the mood was celebratory. What did we celebrate? Ourselves! Back then we loved an excuse to shout woohooooo! I got to bring two virgins. One got on the bus. The other had never smelled flame set to cannabis or been to an amplified concert in her life, so she had zero base for comparison. Later I asked if our behavior had shocked her and she said "you just giggled a lot about small things" and that it was ultimately edifying - that the whole thing was such an alien whirlwind, and loud, and she felt it had taken her weeks to sort. This was the last great run I attended. After this, for my shows, instead of good runs there was one good show, then one good set, and by '93 one good song. SBD trades came up right away for this, somehow. First Set. It isn't just the SBD, Vince was mixed too high FOH, too. The superior video mix reveals the playing. Shakedown does, however, have a couple fine sections. Picasso is rickety in places, as per usual. The rest is delightful. Rooster is solid, though sans excitement peaks, and Bobby switches to his Modulus Pepto for the rest of the show. Stagger Lee is superb. The best I saw, personally, and the best of '90 (well, maybe with 3/18). To Lay is one of only three in '90, and the last for a year and a half. It's sterling - one of the best late examples. Let it Grow is a satisfier and leaves 'em happy for the break. Second Set. With Victim, I thought "finally this song makes some damn sense". It's a powerful version (after seeing 8 or 9 lesser versions). Many heads went from discouraged by the opener to chuffed. Foolish Heart has too many buffed verses to lather about, but good playing. Next comes a bubbly, ticklish Dewiminna that floats (vid mix way better here). He's Gone gets across sweetly with the nice tempo, then the blues jam is excellent. The SBD finally becomes listenable for Drums. I was with a few cats that hadn't yet seen a Dark Star, and when it materialized they acted like they were witnessing a Mars landing or the inauguration of a woman president. This is the 5th Vince Dark Star. It's actually a coda to the version from two nights previous; the second verse. A formless, receding, transitive version. They were scattered in '90 but here we basically got two in three days. Miracle is the best one between 3/21/90 & 6/20/91 (at least). The tempo also helps the worthy Wharf Rat, as does the tight, intricate playing. Jer adds the minimum to Lovelight and makes it quick, ending it before Bobby starts wheezing and squeaking. But it's still celebratory, and naturally a spinner gets onstage at the end (lasting a few seconds). The "encore" follows forthwith. So, we thought there would be a real (second) one, especially after a run and such a good set. Anyway, this Knockin' is picture perfect. 1st Set:  B 2nd Set: A- Overall = 4¼ stars [for vid; deduct one star for SBD] Highlights: Stagger Lee - the one you want from '90 To Lay Me Down - perhaps best late example Victim or the Crime - supposed to be like this Man Smart (Woman Smarter) - bubbly, ticklish He's Gone - well-tempo'd, then blues jam I Need a Miracle - like fireworks a week early Knockin' on Heaven's Door - sweet digestif SOURCES: The 149757_Ultra is the updated SBD, patched and pitched. The show is up on YouTube in a far superior mix (and mostly dark, blurry shots of Jer). The josephsonC640 is a good AUD - just a bit fast; whereas conner_13165, grabski_32022, Darby_120165 & Darby_120164 are all way too fast. The best AUD is 138732_FOB_OTS_Schoeps.
